{
  "texts": [
    "However, the design and implementation of knowledge models require the expertise of domain experts and knowledge engineers, and their capability of handling uncertainty and generalizing is typically limited [16].The recent success of Large Language Models (LLMs) paved the way to LLM-based human activity recognition.",
    "Preliminary results in the state-of-the-art indicate that LLMs implicitly encode the knowledge about human activities, and hence they can potentially be used to cope with labeled data scarcity [32,37].",
    "Given these promising results, we hypothesize that LLMs could be also leveraged to process data from environmental sensors in smart-home environments to reveal the ADLs performed by the monitored subjects, without the need to collect any labeled data.",
    "We expect that LLMs would generalize across individuals and environments without requiring any patient-or environment-specific training data, thus offering a scalable approach.",
    "Moreover, an LLM-based approach would be more flexible in terms of the set of recognizable ADLs (that is usually fixed in supervised approaches).In this work, we propose ADL-LLM, a method leveraging pre-trained LLMs to recognize ADLs in smart-home environments."
  ]
}